{
  "text": "Tropospheric O 3 concentrations are regulated by three processes, i.e. chemical production-destruction, atmospheric transport, and losses to the surface through dry deposition [CITATION_1] . The photolysis of nitrogen dioxide (NO 2 ) in the presence of sunlight is the only known way of producing O 3 in the troposphere [CITATION_2] . O 3 can recombine with nitric oxide (NO) to regenerate NO 2 , which will again undergo photolysis to regenerate O 3 and NO. This continuous process is known as the NO x -dependent photo-stationary state (PSS) and results in no net production or consumption of ozone (null cycle). However, net production of O 3 in the troposphere occurs outside the PSS when peroxy radicals (HO 2 and RO 2 ) alter the PSS by oxidizing NO to produce \"new\" NO 2 [CITATION_3] , resulting in net O 3 production. The main source of these peroxy radicals in the atmosphere is the reaction of the hydroxyl radical (OH • ) with volatile organic compounds (VOCs) or carbon monoxide (CO) [CITATION_4] .",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "97352110",
